{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491036"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:29:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:29:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"811"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/811"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.65,0.02,0.14,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47745"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/811"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32471"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"3463"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9078"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"10994"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13"},{"type":"contributions","id":"124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47745"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old man is admitted to hospital with a two-day history of intermittent right upper quadrant pain. He has no nausea, vomiting, constipation or diarrhoea, nor any weight loss or loss of appetite. He has no significant medical history, including no surgical history, and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft and non-tender with active bowel sounds. A photograph of his eyes is shown (Image 1). Liver function tests show an elevated bilirubin, alkaline phosphatase (ALP), and gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) with normal transaminase levels (AST/ALT). An ultrasound examination of his upper abdomen is performed (Images 2 - 3).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute cholangitis","Choledocholithiasis","Acute viral hepatitis","Acute cholecystitis","Cholangiocarcinoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely underlying cause of this patient\u0027s current illness is \u003Cstrong\u003Echoledocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E. The ultrasound shows the presence of gallstones within the gallbladder, which are strongly associated with choledocholithiasis. Primary stone formation within the common bile duct is rare, and is much more likely to be caused by gallstones that have moved from the gallbladder down the duct system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that transabdominal ultrasound will not necessarily demonstrate gallstones in the common bile duct due to anatomical difficulties (e.g. bowel gas obstructing the view of the distal common bile duct) and is highly dependent on operator proficiency. As such, the absence of a visible stone on ultrasound does not exclude choledocholithiasis in patients with suggestive clinical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by Charcot\u0027s triad of right upper quadrant pain, jaundice, and fever. Given that this patient is afebrile, cholangitis is less likely (though not impossible).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically does not cause jaundice, except in cases with involvement of the common bile duct (such as in Mirizzi syndrome). Furthermore, while there is evidence of cholelithiasis on the gallbladder ultrasound, there is no appreciable thickening of the gallbladder wall or cholecystic sludging which would normally be seen in cholecystitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHepatitis (e.g. \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute viral hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E) is variable in its clinical presentation depending on aetiology, and the history and examination findings may be consistent with hepatitis. However, this is unlikely given the cholestatic picture on liver function tests - hepatitis would much more commonly cause elevated transaminases and normal or mildly elevated ALP and GGT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough jaundice may be the first symptomatic presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003Echolangiocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E, it is likely that the patient would have constitutional symptoms as well. Furthermore, cholangiocarcinoma is a relatively uncommon diagnosis compared to the other options.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gallstone disease should always be considered in patients presenting with acute upper abdominal pain and jaundice."],"references":["Costi R, Gnocchi A, Di Mario F, Sarli L. Diagnosis and management of choledocholithiasis in the golden age of imaging, endoscopy and laparoscopy. World J Gastroenterol. 2014;20(37):13382-13401. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25309071/","Azeem N, Arain M, Freeman M. Choledocolithiasis manifestations, diagnosis and management. UpToDate 2024. Available online: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/choledocholithiasis-clinical-manifestations-diagnosis-and-management#H972627859"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32471"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"811"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"14557"},{"type":"media","id":"14558"},{"type":"media","id":"14559"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"14557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14557"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/edb20858-ad24-428b-9592-f1fbcd388ba2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/edb20858-ad24-428b-9592-f1fbcd388ba2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"14558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14558"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7e6511ca-7b30-479c-a602-5bab960e602b.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7e6511ca-7b30-479c-a602-5bab960e602b.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":535,"height":370}},{"type":"media","id":"14559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/14559"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49ed4e49-5b07-4e30-8849-65e3026ac629.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/49ed4e49-5b07-4e30-8849-65e3026ac629.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":540,"height":376}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32471"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-27T22:23:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-06-27T22:23:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"811"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47745"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes